<section>
	<h2 class="page-header" id="default">Default appearance</h2>
	<p>The browser will show certain elements as a button. However, there is often a lack of visual consistency for each button type. Furthermore, each browser can have a different button default appearance. For example:</p>
	<ul class="list-inline">
		<li><button type="submit">Button</button></li>
		<li><input type="button" value="Input" /></li>
		<li><input type="submit" value="Submit" /></li>
	</ul>

	<pre><code>&lt;ul class=&quot;list-inline&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;button type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Button&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;input type=&quot;button&quot; value=&quot;Input&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;input type=&quot;submit&quot; value=&quot;Submit&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</code></pre>
</section>

<section>
	<h2 class="page-header" id="buttons-tags">Button basics</h2>
	<p>Use the button classes on an <code>&lt;a&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;button&gt;</code>, or <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> element to create visual consistency.</p>
	<ul class="list-inline">
		<li><a class="btn btn-default" href="#" role="button">Link</a></li>
		<li><button class="btn btn-default" type="submit">Button</button></li>
		<li><input class="btn btn-default" type="button" value="Input" /></li>
		<li><input class="btn btn-default" type="submit" value="Submit" /></li>
	</ul>

	<div class="mrgn-tp-lg">
		<pre><code>&lt;ul class=&quot;list-inline&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;a class=&quot;btn btn-default&quot; href=&quot;#&quot; role=&quot;button&quot;&gt;Link&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;button class=&quot;btn btn-default&quot; type=&quot;submit&quot;&gt;Button&lt;/button&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;input class=&quot;btn btn-default&quot; type=&quot;button&quot; value=&quot;Input&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;input class=&quot;btn btn-default&quot; type=&quot;submit&quot; value=&quot;Submit&quot; /&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</code></pre>
	</div>

	<section class="alert alert-info">
		<h3>Cross-browser rendering</h3>
		<p>As a best practice, <strong>we highly recommend using the <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> element whenever possible</strong> to ensure matching cross-browser rendering.</p>
		<p>Among other things, there's <a href="https://bugzilla.mozilla.org/show_bug.cgi?id=697451">a Firefox bug</a> that prevents us from setting the <code>line-height</code> of <code>&lt;input&gt;</code>-based buttons, causing them to not exactly match the height of other buttons on Firefox.</p>
	</section>

